</div><div class="info-panel__citations info-panel__item"><a href="#tab-citations" class="btn btn--inverse btn--slim" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="View Citations" aria-label="View Citations"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-format_quote"></i></a></div><div class="info-panel__formats info-panel__item"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="Go to purchase options" aria-label="Go to purchase options"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="link-text">Get Access</span></a></div></div></div></div></header><div data-core-nav="header" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-nav-wrapper core-container" aria-label="Article navigation"><div><button aria-controls="article_sections_menu" aria-expanded="false" aria-label="Toggle section navigation menu"><i class="icon-list" aria-hidden="true"></i><span>Contents</span></button><nav id="article_sections_menu" aria-label="Contents" data-core-nav="article"><ul><li><a href="#abstract">Abstract</a></li><li><a href="#core-sec-figures">Figures</a></li><li><a href="#bibliography">References</a></li></ul></nav></div><nav id="article_collateral_menu"><ul class="collateral-pill" data-core-nav="collateral"><li><a href="#core-collateral-info" aria-controls="core-collateral-info" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Information & Authors" title="Information & Authors" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-info"></i><span class="sr-only">Information & Authors</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-metrics" aria-controls="core-collateral-metrics" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Metrics & Citations" title="Metrics & Citations" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-metrics"></i><span class="sr-only">Metrics & Citations</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-controls="core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Get Access" title="Get Access" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="sr-only">Get Access</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-references" aria-controls="core-collateral-references" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="References" title="References" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-references"></i><span class="sr-only">References</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-figures" aria-controls="core-collateral-figures" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Figures" title="Figures" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-photo"></i><span class="sr-only">Figures</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-tables" aria-controls="core-collateral-tables" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Tables" title="Tables" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-table"></i><span class="sr-only">Tables</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-media" aria-controls="core-collateral-media" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Media" title="Media" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-play-circle-filled"></i><span class="sr-only">Media</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-share" aria-controls="core-collateral-share" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Share" title="Share" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-share"></i><span class="sr-only">Share</span></a></li></ul></nav></div></div><div data-core-wrapper="content"><div id="abstracts" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="abstract" property="abstract" typeof="Text" role="doc-abstract"><h2 property="name">Abstract</h2><div role="paragraph">Cardiac tumors in children are rare, are more commonly benign, and differ in types when compared with those in adults. Rhabdomyoma, teratoma, and fibroma are the most common cardiac tumors in fetuses and neonates. In infants and children, the most common cardiac tumors are rhabdomyoma and fibroma, which are benign primary cardiac tumors, whereas in adults, thrombus is the most common cardiac mass and myxoma is the most common primary cardiac tumor. Sarcomas are the most common primary malignant cardiac tumors in both children and adults. Metastatic cardiac tumors are less common in children than in adults and include sarcoma, lymphoma, testicular cancer, and Wilms tumor. Patients with cardiac tumors can be asymptomatic or may present with murmur, arrhythmia, heart failure, or sudden death. Echocardiography is the primary modality for initial evaluation of symptomatic patients. Cardiac magnetic resonance imaging provides further characterization of cardiac masses and tumors for diagnostic purposes and can be used to assess cardiac and extracardiac involvement for treatment planning. Treatment varies from conservative management or surgical resection to transplantation, depending on the diagnosis and the patient’s symptoms. Rhabdomyoma typically regresses spontaneously during early childhood and does not require surgical intervention if asymptomatic. However, fibroma is generally resected because it does not regress. An understanding of the types of cardiac tumors that occur in infants and children, their clinical implications and associations, and their imaging appearances will facilitate patient management.</div><div role="paragraph">©RSNA, 2014</div></section></div></div><section id="bodymatter" data-extent="bodymatter" property="articleBody" typeof="Text"><div class="core-container"><section aria-labelledby="denial-block-title" class="denial-block "><h2 id="denial-block-title" class="denial-block__title">Get full access to this article</h2><p class="denial-block__text">View all available purchase options and get full access to this article.</p><div class="denial-block__cta"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span>Get Access</span></a></div><footer class="denial-block__footer"><span>Already a Subscriber? </span><span>Sign in as an </span><a href="/action/showLogin?redirectUri=/doi/10.1148/rg.344135163">individual</a><span> or via your </span><a href="/action/ssostart?uri=/doi/10.1148/rg.344135163">institution</a></footer></section></div></section><section id="backmatter" data-extent="backmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="core-sec-figures" data-type="figures"><h2>Figures</h2><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.344135163/asset/images/large/rg.344135163.fig1a.jpeg" height="651" width="733" aria-labelledby="fig1a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1a</span> Rhabdomyoma. <b>(a)</b> Transverse US image obtained in a fetus at 22 weeks of gestation shows a hyperechoic mass (*) in the interventricular septum. <i>L</i> = lung. <b>(b, c)</b> Axial half-Fourier acquisition single-shot turbo spin-echo (HASTE) (Siemens Healthcare, Erlangen, Germany) <b>(b)</b> and coronal true fast imaging with steady-state precession (FISP) <b>(c)</b> fetal MR images obtained at 34 weeks of gestation in the same patient as in <b>a</b> show a large mass (*) arising from the interventricular septum, consistent with a rhabdomyoma. <i>L</i> = lung. <b>(d)</b> Oblique postnatal echocardiogram shows a large echogenic rhabdomyoma (*) in the ventricular septum that fills almost the entire right ventricle <i>(RV)</i> and a portion of the left ventricle <i>(LV)</i>. On serial echocardiograms obtained through 2 years of age (not shown), the rhabdomyoma has been progressively decreasing in size.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.344135163&amp;id=fig1a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.344135163/asset/images/large/rg.344135163.fig1b.jpeg" height="651" width="743" aria-labelledby="fig1b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1b</span> Rhabdomyoma. <b>(a)</b> Transverse US image obtained in a fetus at 22 weeks of gestation shows a hyperechoic mass (*) in the interventricular septum. <i>L</i> = lung. <b>(b, c)</b> Axial half-Fourier acquisition single-shot turbo spin-echo (HASTE) (Siemens Healthcare, Erlangen, Germany) <b>(b)</b> and coronal true fast imaging with steady-state precession (FISP) <b>(c)</b> fetal MR images obtained at 34 weeks of gestation in the same patient as in <b>a</b> show a large mass (*) arising from the interventricular septum, consistent with a rhabdomyoma. <i>L</i> = lung. <b>(d)</b> Oblique postnatal echocardiogram shows a large echogenic rhabdomyoma (*) in the ventricular septum that fills almost the entire right ventricle <i>(RV)</i> and a portion of the left ventricle <i>(LV)</i>. On serial echocardiograms obtained through 2 years of age (not shown), the rhabdomyoma has been progressively decreasing in size.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.344135163&amp;id=fig1b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.344135163/asset/images/large/rg.344135163.fig1c.jpeg" height="645" width="738" aria-labelledby="fig1c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1c</span> Rhabdomyoma. <b>(a)</b> Transverse US image obtained in a fetus at 22 weeks of gestation shows a hyperechoic mass (*) in the interventricular septum. <i>L</i> = lung. <b>(b, c)</b> Axial half-Fourier acquisition single-shot turbo spin-echo (HASTE) (Siemens Healthcare, Erlangen, Germany) <b>(b)</b> and coronal true fast imaging with steady-state precession (FISP) <b>(c)</b> fetal MR images obtained at 34 weeks of gestation in the same patient as in <b>a</b> show a large mass (*) arising from the interventricular septum, consistent with a rhabdomyoma. <i>L</i> = lung. <b>(d)</b> Oblique postnatal echocardiogram shows a large echogenic rhabdomyoma (*) in the ventricular septum that fills almost the entire right ventricle <i>(RV)</i> and a portion of the left ventricle <i>(LV)</i>. On serial echocardiograms obtained through 2 years of age (not shown), the rhabdomyoma has been progressively decreasing in size.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.344135163&amp;id=fig1c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.344135163/asset/images/large/rg.344135163.fig1d.jpeg" height="645" width="738" aria-labelledby="fig1d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1d</span> Rhabdomyoma. <b>(a)</b> Transverse US image obtained in a fetus at 22 weeks of gestation shows a hyperechoic mass (*) in the interventricular septum. <i>L</i> = lung. <b>(b, c)</b> Axial half-Fourier acquisition single-shot turbo spin-echo (HASTE) (Siemens Healthcare, Erlangen, Germany) <b>(b)</b> and coronal true fast imaging with steady-state precession (FISP) <b>(c)</b> fetal MR images obtained at 34 weeks of gestation in the same patient as in <b>a</b> show a large mass (*) arising from the interventricular septum, consistent with a rhabdomyoma. <i>L</i> = lung. <b>(d)</b> Oblique postnatal echocardiogram shows a large echogenic rhabdomyoma (*) in the ventricular septum that fills almost the entire right ventricle <i>(RV)</i> and a portion of the left ventricle <i>(LV)</i>. On serial echocardiograms obtained through 2 years of age (not shown), the rhabdomyoma has been progressively decreasing in size.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.344135163&amp;id=fig1d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.344135163/asset/images/large/rg.344135163.fig2a.jpeg" height="789" width="737" aria-labelledby="fig2a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2a</span> Rhabdomyoma in a 37-week-gestation fetus with a large intrathoracic mass seen at antenatal survey US. <b>(a)</b> Transaxial true FISP fetal MR image demonstrates a large left ventricular mass (*). <b>(b)</b> Transaxial true FISP image of the brain shows a T2-hypointense subependymal nodule in the right lateral ventricle (arrow). Cortical tubers were also present (not shown). The infant died of arrhythmia, cardiac failure, and pulmonary hypoplasia 1 day after birth. Autopsy confirmed a large cardiac rhabdomyoma, cortical tubers, and subependymal nodules, findings consistent with tuberous sclerosis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.344135163&amp;id=fig2a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.344135163/asset/images/large/rg.344135163.fig2b.jpeg" height="789" width="737" aria-labelledby="fig2b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2b</span> Rhabdomyoma in a 37-week-gestation fetus with a large intrathoracic mass seen at antenatal survey US. <b>(a)</b> Transaxial true FISP fetal MR image demonstrates a large left ventricular mass (*). <b>(b)</b> Transaxial true FISP image of the brain shows a T2-hypointense subependymal nodule in the right lateral ventricle (arrow). Cortical tubers were also present (not shown). The infant died of arrhythmia, cardiac failure, and pulmonary hypoplasia 1 day after birth. Autopsy confirmed a large cardiac rhabdomyoma, cortical tubers, and subependymal nodules, findings consistent with tuberous sclerosis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.344135163&amp;id=fig2b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.344135163/asset/images/large/rg.344135163.fig3a.jpeg" height="655" width="738" aria-labelledby="fig3a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3a</span> Fibroma in a 4-month-old female infant with a heart murmur. <b>(a–c)</b> Transaxial black blood <b>(a)</b>, short-axis two-chamber cine <b>(b)</b>, and transaxial contrast-enhanced <b>(c)</b> MR images show a large isointense and slightly hypointense mass (*) centered in the right ventricular free wall. It exerts mass effect on the right ventricular outflow tract <i>(RVOT)</i>. The mass is encapsulated (arrows in <b>c</b>) and slowly enhances diffusely. A moderate pericardial effusion is also seen (arrowheads in <b>b</b>). <i>LV</i> = left ventricle. <b>(d)</b> Two-dimensional gray-scale US image and color flow map show a large right ventricular mass (*) filling the right ventricle and causing flow obstruction through the tricuspid valve. The patient underwent surgical resection, and pathologic analysis confirmed cardiac fibroma.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.344135163&amp;id=fig3a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.344135163/asset/images/large/rg.344135163.fig3b.jpeg" height="655" width="738" aria-labelledby="fig3b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3b</span> Fibroma in a 4-month-old female infant with a heart murmur. <b>(a–c)</b> Transaxial black blood <b>(a)</b>, short-axis two-chamber cine <b>(b)</b>, and transaxial contrast-enhanced <b>(c)</b> MR images show a large isointense and slightly hypointense mass (*) centered in the right ventricular free wall. It exerts mass effect on the right ventricular outflow tract <i>(RVOT)</i>. The mass is encapsulated (arrows in <b>c</b>) and slowly enhances diffusely. A moderate pericardial effusion is also seen (arrowheads in <b>b</b>). <i>LV</i> = left ventricle. <b>(d)</b> Two-dimensional gray-scale US image and color flow map show a large right ventricular mass (*) filling the right ventricle and causing flow obstruction through the tricuspid valve. The patient underwent surgical resection, and pathologic analysis confirmed cardiac fibroma.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.344135163&amp;id=fig3b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.344135163/asset/images/large/rg.344135163.fig3c.jpeg" height="652" width="735" aria-labelledby="fig3c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3c</span> Fibroma in a 4-month-old female infant with a heart murmur. <b>(a–c)</b> Transaxial black blood <b>(a)</b>, short-axis two-chamber cine <b>(b)</b>, and transaxial contrast-enhanced <b>(c)</b> MR images show a large isointense and slightly hypointense mass (*) centered in the right ventricular free wall. It exerts mass effect on the right ventricular outflow tract <i>(RVOT)</i>. The mass is encapsulated (arrows in <b>c</b>) and slowly enhances diffusely. A moderate pericardial effusion is also seen (arrowheads in <b>b</b>). <i>LV</i> = left ventricle. <b>(d)</b> Two-dimensional gray-scale US image and color flow map show a large right ventricular mass (*) filling the right ventricle and causing flow obstruction through the tricuspid valve. The patient underwent surgical resection, and pathologic analysis confirmed cardiac fibroma.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.344135163&amp;id=fig3c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.344135163/asset/images/large/rg.344135163.fig3d.jpeg" height="652" width="740" aria-labelledby="fig3d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3d</span> Fibroma in a 4-month-old female infant with a heart murmur. <b>(a–c)</b> Transaxial black blood <b>(a)</b>, short-axis two-chamber cine <b>(b)</b>, and transaxial contrast-enhanced <b>(c)</b> MR images show a large isointense and slightly hypointense mass (*) centered in the right ventricular free wall. It exerts mass effect on the right ventricular outflow tract <i>(RVOT)</i>. The mass is encapsulated (arrows in <b>c</b>) and slowly enhances diffusely. A moderate pericardial effusion is also seen (arrowheads in <b>b</b>). <i>LV</i> = left ventricle. <b>(d)</b> Two-dimensional gray-scale US image and color flow map show a large right ventricular mass (*) filling the right ventricle and causing flow obstruction through the tricuspid valve. The patient underwent surgical resection, and pathologic analysis confirmed cardiac fibroma.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.344135163&amp;id=fig3d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.344135163/asset/images/large/rg.344135163.fig4a.jpeg" height="655" width="737" aria-labelledby="fig4a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4a</span> Fibroma in a 5-month-old female infant with Gorlin syndrome and a left ventricular mass. Transaxial black blood <b>(a)</b> and bright blood <b>(b)</b> MR images and short-axis two-chamber cine nonenhanced <b>(c)</b> and contrast-enhanced <b>(d)</b> MR images show a large mildly heterogeneous mass (*) centered in the interventricular septum and anterior wall of the left ventricle <i>(LV)</i>. The mass shows progressive heterogeneous enhancement in <b>d</b>. The appearance of the mass is consistent with fibroma. The fibroma is not amenable to surgical resection because of its extent. An epicardial pacer system was placed, given the high risk of malignant arrhythmia. The patient underwent orthotopic heart transplantation 2 weeks later, and explant pathologic analysis confirmed cardiac fibroma. <i>Ao</i> = aorta, <i>LA</i> = left atrium, <i>RV</i> = right ventricle, <i>SVC</i> = superior vena cava.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.344135163&amp;id=fig4a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.344135163/asset/images/large/rg.344135163.fig4b.jpeg" height="655" width="737" aria-labelledby="fig4b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4b</span> Fibroma in a 5-month-old female infant with Gorlin syndrome and a left ventricular mass. Transaxial black blood <b>(a)</b> and bright blood <b>(b)</b> MR images and short-axis two-chamber cine nonenhanced <b>(c)</b> and contrast-enhanced <b>(d)</b> MR images show a large mildly heterogeneous mass (*) centered in the interventricular septum and anterior wall of the left ventricle <i>(LV)</i>. The mass shows progressive heterogeneous enhancement in <b>d</b>. The appearance of the mass is consistent with fibroma. The fibroma is not amenable to surgical resection because of its extent. An epicardial pacer system was placed, given the high risk of malignant arrhythmia. The patient underwent orthotopic heart transplantation 2 weeks later, and explant pathologic analysis confirmed cardiac fibroma. <i>Ao</i> = aorta, <i>LA</i> = left atrium, <i>RV</i> = right ventricle, <i>SVC</i> = superior vena cava.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.344135163&amp;id=fig4b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.344135163/asset/images/large/rg.344135163.fig4c.jpeg" height="639" width="737" aria-labelledby="fig4c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4c</span> Fibroma in a 5-month-old female infant with Gorlin syndrome and a left ventricular mass. Transaxial black blood <b>(a)</b> and bright blood <b>(b)</b> MR images and short-axis two-chamber cine nonenhanced <b>(c)</b> and contrast-enhanced <b>(d)</b> MR images show a large mildly heterogeneous mass (*) centered in the interventricular septum and anterior wall of the left ventricle <i>(LV)</i>. The mass shows progressive heterogeneous enhancement in <b>d</b>. The appearance of the mass is consistent with fibroma. The fibroma is not amenable to surgical resection because of its extent. An epicardial pacer system was placed, given the high risk of malignant arrhythmia. The patient underwent orthotopic heart transplantation 2 weeks later, and explant pathologic analysis confirmed cardiac fibroma. <i>Ao</i> = aorta, <i>LA</i> = left atrium, <i>RV</i> = right ventricle, <i>SVC</i> = superior vena cava.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.344135163&amp;id=fig4c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.344135163/asset/images/large/rg.344135163.fig4d.jpeg" height="639" width="737" aria-labelledby="fig4d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4d</span> Fibroma in a 5-month-old female infant with Gorlin syndrome and a left ventricular mass. Transaxial black blood <b>(a)</b> and bright blood <b>(b)</b> MR images and short-axis two-chamber cine nonenhanced <b>(c)</b> and contrast-enhanced <b>(d)</b> MR images show a large mildly heterogeneous mass (*) centered in the interventricular septum and anterior wall of the left ventricle <i>(LV)</i>. The mass shows progressive heterogeneous enhancement in <b>d</b>. The appearance of the mass is consistent with fibroma. The fibroma is not amenable to surgical resection because of its extent. An epicardial pacer system was placed, given the high risk of malignant arrhythmia. The patient underwent orthotopic heart transplantation 2 weeks later, and explant pathologic analysis confirmed cardiac fibroma. <i>Ao</i> = aorta, <i>LA</i> = left atrium, <i>RV</i> = right ventricle, <i>SVC</i> = superior vena cava.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.344135163&amp;id=fig4d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.344135163/asset/images/large/rg.344135163.fig5a.jpeg" height="691" width="737" aria-labelledby="fig5a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5a</span> IMFT in a 7-year-old boy with a heart murmur. <i>PA</i> = pulmonary artery. <b>(a)</b> Transaxial CT image shows a predominantly low-attenuation lesion (*) centered in the right ventricular outflow tract and main pulmonary artery. <i>Ao</i> = aorta. <b>(b, c)</b> Sagittal black blood <b>(b)</b> and transaxial contrast-enhanced <b>(c)</b> MR images show the nonenhancing mass (*), which is likely attached to the undersurface of the pulmonic valve. <i>LV</i> = left ventricle, <i>RV</i> = right ventricle. <b>(d)</b> Echocardiogram shows a mass (*) attached to the pulmonary valve in the right ventricular outflow tract <i>(RVOT)</i> causing flow obstruction. At surgery, the somewhat fibrous mass was found to emanate from the right ventricular free wall and pulmonic valve. Pathologic analysis of the excised mass confirmed an IMFT.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.344135163&amp;id=fig5a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.344135163/asset/images/large/rg.344135163.fig5b.jpeg" height="691" width="737" aria-labelledby="fig5b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5b</span> IMFT in a 7-year-old boy with a heart murmur. <i>PA</i> = pulmonary artery. <b>(a)</b> Transaxial CT image shows a predominantly low-attenuation lesion (*) centered in the right ventricular outflow tract and main pulmonary artery. <i>Ao</i> = aorta. <b>(b, c)</b> Sagittal black blood <b>(b)</b> and transaxial contrast-enhanced <b>(c)</b> MR images show the nonenhancing mass (*), which is likely attached to the undersurface of the pulmonic valve. <i>LV</i> = left ventricle, <i>RV</i> = right ventricle. <b>(d)</b> Echocardiogram shows a mass (*) attached to the pulmonary valve in the right ventricular outflow tract <i>(RVOT)</i> causing flow obstruction. At surgery, the somewhat fibrous mass was found to emanate from the right ventricular free wall and pulmonic valve. Pathologic analysis of the excised mass confirmed an IMFT.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.344135163&amp;id=fig5b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.344135163/asset/images/large/rg.344135163.fig5c.jpeg" height="673" width="718" aria-labelledby="fig5c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5c</span> IMFT in a 7-year-old boy with a heart murmur. <i>PA</i> = pulmonary artery. <b>(a)</b> Transaxial CT image shows a predominantly low-attenuation lesion (*) centered in the right ventricular outflow tract and main pulmonary artery. <i>Ao</i> = aorta. <b>(b, c)</b> Sagittal black blood <b>(b)</b> and transaxial contrast-enhanced <b>(c)</b> MR images show the nonenhancing mass (*), which is likely attached to the undersurface of the pulmonic valve. <i>LV</i> = left ventricle, <i>RV</i> = right ventricle. <b>(d)</b> Echocardiogram shows a mass (*) attached to the pulmonary valve in the right ventricular outflow tract <i>(RVOT)</i> causing flow obstruction. At surgery, the somewhat fibrous mass was found to emanate from the right ventricular free wall and pulmonic valve. Pathologic analysis of the excised mass confirmed an IMFT.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.344135163&amp;id=fig5c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.344135163/asset/images/large/rg.344135163.fig5d.jpeg" height="673" width="757" aria-labelledby="fig5d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5d</span> IMFT in a 7-year-old boy with a heart murmur. <i>PA</i> = pulmonary artery. <b>(a)</b> Transaxial CT image shows a predominantly low-attenuation lesion (*) centered in the right ventricular outflow tract and main pulmonary artery. <i>Ao</i> = aorta. <b>(b, c)</b> Sagittal black blood <b>(b)</b> and transaxial contrast-enhanced <b>(c)</b> MR images show the nonenhancing mass (*), which is likely attached to the undersurface of the pulmonic valve. <i>LV</i> = left ventricle, <i>RV</i> = right ventricle. <b>(d)</b> Echocardiogram shows a mass (*) attached to the pulmonary valve in the right ventricular outflow tract <i>(RVOT)</i> causing flow obstruction. At surgery, the somewhat fibrous mass was found to emanate from the right ventricular free wall and pulmonic valve. Pathologic analysis of the excised mass confirmed an IMFT.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.344135163&amp;id=fig5d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.344135163/asset/images/large/rg.344135163.fig6a.jpeg" height="799" width="800" aria-labelledby="fig6a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6a</span> Intrapericardial teratoma. <b>(a)</b> Long-axis four-chamber US image of a fetus at 23 weeks of gestation shows a predominantly solid heterogeneous mass (*) arising at the base of the heart, with a pericardial effusion (arrows). <i>L</i> = lung, <i>RV</i> = right ventricle. (Courtesy of Beverly G. Coleman, MD, Children’s Hospital of Philadelphia, Philadelphia, Pa.) <b>(b, c)</b> Transaxial true FISP <b>(b)</b> and coronal HASTE <b>(c)</b> fetal MR images show a heterogeneous intrapericardial mass (*) containing multiple cystic foci, with a small pericardial effusion (arrows in <b>b</b>) surrounding the mass and heart. Open fetal resection of the mass was performed at 24 weeks of gestation, and pathologic analysis confirmed teratoma. (<a href="#fig6b">Fig 6b</a> and <a href="#fig6c">6c</a> courtesy of Diego Jaramillo, MD, Children’s Hospital of Philadelphia, Philadelphia, Pa.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.344135163&amp;id=fig6a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.344135163/asset/images/large/rg.344135163.fig6b.jpeg" height="737" width="737" aria-labelledby="fig6b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6b</span> Intrapericardial teratoma. <b>(a)</b> Long-axis four-chamber US image of a fetus at 23 weeks of gestation shows a predominantly solid heterogeneous mass (*) arising at the base of the heart, with a pericardial effusion (arrows). <i>L</i> = lung, <i>RV</i> = right ventricle. (Courtesy of Beverly G. Coleman, MD, Children’s Hospital of Philadelphia, Philadelphia, Pa.) <b>(b, c)</b> Transaxial true FISP <b>(b)</b> and coronal HASTE <b>(c)</b> fetal MR images show a heterogeneous intrapericardial mass (*) containing multiple cystic foci, with a small pericardial effusion (arrows in <b>b</b>) surrounding the mass and heart. Open fetal resection of the mass was performed at 24 weeks of gestation, and pathologic analysis confirmed teratoma. (<a href="#fig6b">Fig 6b</a> and <a href="#fig6c">6c</a> courtesy of Diego Jaramillo, MD, Children’s Hospital of Philadelphia, Philadelphia, Pa.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.344135163&amp;id=fig6b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.344135163/asset/images/large/rg.344135163.fig6c.jpeg" height="737" width="737" aria-labelledby="fig6c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6c</span> Intrapericardial teratoma. <b>(a)</b> Long-axis four-chamber US image of a fetus at 23 weeks of gestation shows a predominantly solid heterogeneous mass (*) arising at the base of the heart, with a pericardial effusion (arrows). <i>L</i> = lung, <i>RV</i> = right ventricle. (Courtesy of Beverly G. Coleman, MD, Children’s Hospital of Philadelphia, Philadelphia, Pa.) <b>(b, c)</b> Transaxial true FISP <b>(b)</b> and coronal HASTE <b>(c)</b> fetal MR images show a heterogeneous intrapericardial mass (*) containing multiple cystic foci, with a small pericardial effusion (arrows in <b>b</b>) surrounding the mass and heart. Open fetal resection of the mass was performed at 24 weeks of gestation, and pathologic analysis confirmed teratoma. (<a href="#fig6b">Fig 6b</a> and <a href="#fig6c">6c</a> courtesy of Diego Jaramillo, MD, Children’s Hospital of Philadelphia, Philadelphia, Pa.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.344135163&amp;id=fig6c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.344135163/asset/images/large/rg.344135163.fig7a.jpeg" height="632" width="737" aria-labelledby="fig7a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7a</span> Primary cardiac synovial cell sarcoma in a 14-year-old male adolescent after orthotopic heart transplant for primary cardiac synovial cell sarcoma. <b>(a)</b> Coronal CT image shows a mass (*) in the right atrium <i>(RA)</i>. <b>(b, c)</b> Transaxial black blood <b>(b)</b> and contrast-enhanced <b>(c)</b> MR images demonstrate an enhancing lobulated soft-tissue mass (*) at the inferior cavoatrial junction that extends into the right atrium <i>(RA)</i>, a finding consistent with tumor recurrence. <i>RV</i> = right ventricle. <b>(d)</b> Echocardiogram shows a large echogenic mass (*) filling the right atrium. Biopsy results confirmed recurrent synovial cell sarcoma at the inferior vena cava suture line from heart transplantation. The patient underwent tumor debulking because he had received the maximum chemotherapeutic dose. <i>LA</i> = left atrium, <i>LV</i> = left ventricle.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.344135163&amp;id=fig7a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.344135163/asset/images/large/rg.344135163.fig7b.jpeg" height="632" width="738" aria-labelledby="fig7b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7b</span> Primary cardiac synovial cell sarcoma in a 14-year-old male adolescent after orthotopic heart transplant for primary cardiac synovial cell sarcoma. <b>(a)</b> Coronal CT image shows a mass (*) in the right atrium <i>(RA)</i>. <b>(b, c)</b> Transaxial black blood <b>(b)</b> and contrast-enhanced <b>(c)</b> MR images demonstrate an enhancing lobulated soft-tissue mass (*) at the inferior cavoatrial junction that extends into the right atrium <i>(RA)</i>, a finding consistent with tumor recurrence. <i>RV</i> = right ventricle. <b>(d)</b> Echocardiogram shows a large echogenic mass (*) filling the right atrium. Biopsy results confirmed recurrent synovial cell sarcoma at the inferior vena cava suture line from heart transplantation. The patient underwent tumor debulking because he had received the maximum chemotherapeutic dose. <i>LA</i> = left atrium, <i>LV</i> = left ventricle.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.344135163&amp;id=fig7b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.344135163/asset/images/large/rg.344135163.fig7c.jpeg" height="644" width="750" aria-labelledby="fig7c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7c</span> Primary cardiac synovial cell sarcoma in a 14-year-old male adolescent after orthotopic heart transplant for primary cardiac synovial cell sarcoma. <b>(a)</b> Coronal CT image shows a mass (*) in the right atrium <i>(RA)</i>. <b>(b, c)</b> Transaxial black blood <b>(b)</b> and contrast-enhanced <b>(c)</b> MR images demonstrate an enhancing lobulated soft-tissue mass (*) at the inferior cavoatrial junction that extends into the right atrium <i>(RA)</i>, a finding consistent with tumor recurrence. <i>RV</i> = right ventricle. <b>(d)</b> Echocardiogram shows a large echogenic mass (*) filling the right atrium. Biopsy results confirmed recurrent synovial cell sarcoma at the inferior vena cava suture line from heart transplantation. The patient underwent tumor debulking because he had received the maximum chemotherapeutic dose. <i>LA</i> = left atrium, <i>LV</i> = left ventricle.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.344135163&amp;id=fig7c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.344135163/asset/images/large/rg.344135163.fig7d.jpeg" height="644" width="724" aria-labelledby="fig7d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7d</span> Primary cardiac synovial cell sarcoma in a 14-year-old male adolescent after orthotopic heart transplant for primary cardiac synovial cell sarcoma. <b>(a)</b> Coronal CT image shows a mass (*) in the right atrium <i>(RA)</i>. <b>(b, c)</b> Transaxial black blood <b>(b)</b> and contrast-enhanced <b>(c)</b> MR images demonstrate an enhancing lobulated soft-tissue mass (*) at the inferior cavoatrial junction that extends into the right atrium <i>(RA)</i>, a finding consistent with tumor recurrence. <i>RV</i> = right ventricle. <b>(d)</b> Echocardiogram shows a large echogenic mass (*) filling the right atrium. Biopsy results confirmed recurrent synovial cell sarcoma at the inferior vena cava suture line from heart transplantation. The patient underwent tumor debulking because he had received the maximum chemotherapeutic dose. <i>LA</i> = left atrium, <i>LV</i> = left ventricle.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.344135163&amp;id=fig7d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.344135163/asset/images/large/rg.344135163.fig8a.jpeg" height="711" width="800" aria-labelledby="fig8a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8a</span> Lymphoma in a 9-year-old girl with worsening facial swelling and venous distention of the chest and face. <b>(a, b)</b> Transaxial <b>(a)</b> and sagittal <b>(b)</b> CT images show a large intracardiac mass (*) predominantly in the right atrium <i>(RA)</i>. A portion of the mass extends into the right ventricle (<i>RV)</i> (arrows in <b>a</b>). There is extensive venous obstruction due to mass extension into the superior vena cava, both brachiocephalic veins, and the azygos vein (<i>Az</i>). A large anterior mediastinal soft-tissue component (arrows in <b>b</b>) containing calcifications is also seen. <b>(c)</b> Echocardiogram shows the large mass (*) extending from the superior vena cava and filling almost the entire right atrium <i>(RA)</i>. Biopsy of the right atrial mass demonstrated large B-cell lymphoma, and the patient underwent chemotherapy. <i>LA</i> = left atrium, <i>LV</i> = left ventricle, <i>RV</i> = right ventricle.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.344135163&amp;id=fig8a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.344135163/asset/images/large/rg.344135163.fig8b.jpeg" height="655" width="737" aria-labelledby="fig8b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8b</span> Lymphoma in a 9-year-old girl with worsening facial swelling and venous distention of the chest and face. <b>(a, b)</b> Transaxial <b>(a)</b> and sagittal <b>(b)</b> CT images show a large intracardiac mass (*) predominantly in the right atrium <i>(RA)</i>. A portion of the mass extends into the right ventricle (<i>RV)</i> (arrows in <b>a</b>). There is extensive venous obstruction due to mass extension into the superior vena cava, both brachiocephalic veins, and the azygos vein (<i>Az</i>). A large anterior mediastinal soft-tissue component (arrows in <b>b</b>) containing calcifications is also seen. <b>(c)</b> Echocardiogram shows the large mass (*) extending from the superior vena cava and filling almost the entire right atrium <i>(RA)</i>. Biopsy of the right atrial mass demonstrated large B-cell lymphoma, and the patient underwent chemotherapy. <i>LA</i> = left atrium, <i>LV</i> = left ventricle, <i>RV</i> = right ventricle.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.344135163&amp;id=fig8b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.344135163/asset/images/large/rg.344135163.fig8c.jpeg" height="655" width="737" aria-labelledby="fig8c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8c</span> Lymphoma in a 9-year-old girl with worsening facial swelling and venous distention of the chest and face. <b>(a, b)</b> Transaxial <b>(a)</b> and sagittal <b>(b)</b> CT images show a large intracardiac mass (*) predominantly in the right atrium <i>(RA)</i>. A portion of the mass extends into the right ventricle (<i>RV)</i> (arrows in <b>a</b>). There is extensive venous obstruction due to mass extension into the superior vena cava, both brachiocephalic veins, and the azygos vein (<i>Az</i>). A large anterior mediastinal soft-tissue component (arrows in <b>b</b>) containing calcifications is also seen. <b>(c)</b> Echocardiogram shows the large mass (*) extending from the superior vena cava and filling almost the entire right atrium <i>(RA)</i>. Biopsy of the right atrial mass demonstrated large B-cell lymphoma, and the patient underwent chemotherapy. <i>LA</i> = left atrium, <i>LV</i> = left ventricle, <i>RV</i> = right ventricle.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.344135163&amp;id=fig8c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.344135163/asset/images/large/rg.344135163.fig9a.jpeg" height="711" width="800" aria-labelledby="fig9a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9a</span> Metastatic leiomyosarcoma in an 18-year-old man with chest pain. Transaxial bright blood <b>(a)</b>, long-axis four-chamber cine <b>(b)</b>, and transaxial delayed contrast-enhanced <b>(c</b>) MR images show a multilobulated enhancing mass (*) in the left atrium <i>(LA)</i>, which involves the posterolateral left atrial wall and left pulmonary vein. An enhancing pleural mass (arrows in <b>a</b> and <b>c</b>) is also seen in the left hemithorax, and there were multiple pulmonary nodules (not shown). Pathologic analysis of the excised left atrial mass confirmed metastatic leiomyosarcoma, likely from primary lung sarcoma. <i>LV</i> = left ventricle.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.344135163&amp;id=fig9a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.344135163/asset/images/large/rg.344135163.fig9b.jpeg" height="621" width="737" aria-labelledby="fig9b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9b</span> Metastatic leiomyosarcoma in an 18-year-old man with chest pain. Transaxial bright blood <b>(a)</b>, long-axis four-chamber cine <b>(b)</b>, and transaxial delayed contrast-enhanced <b>(c</b>) MR images show a multilobulated enhancing mass (*) in the left atrium <i>(LA)</i>, which involves the posterolateral left atrial wall and left pulmonary vein. An enhancing pleural mass (arrows in <b>a</b> and <b>c</b>) is also seen in the left hemithorax, and there were multiple pulmonary nodules (not shown). Pathologic analysis of the excised left atrial mass confirmed metastatic leiomyosarcoma, likely from primary lung sarcoma. <i>LV</i> = left ventricle.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.344135163&amp;id=fig9b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.344135163/asset/images/large/rg.344135163.fig9c.jpeg" height="621" width="737" aria-labelledby="fig9c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9c</span> Metastatic leiomyosarcoma in an 18-year-old man with chest pain. Transaxial bright blood <b>(a)</b>, long-axis four-chamber cine <b>(b)</b>, and transaxial delayed contrast-enhanced <b>(c</b>) MR images show a multilobulated enhancing mass (*) in the left atrium <i>(LA)</i>, which involves the posterolateral left atrial wall and left pulmonary vein. An enhancing pleural mass (arrows in <b>a</b> and <b>c</b>) is also seen in the left hemithorax, and there were multiple pulmonary nodules (not shown). Pathologic analysis of the excised left atrial mass confirmed metastatic leiomyosarcoma, likely from primary lung sarcoma. <i>LV</i> = left ventricle.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.344135163&amp;id=fig9c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.344135163/asset/images/large/rg.344135163.fig10a.jpeg" height="581" width="737" aria-labelledby="fig10a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10a</span> Thrombus in a 7-year-old girl with hemoglobin SS disease and a right atrial mass seen at routine echocardiography. <i>RV</i> = right ventricle. <b>(a)</b> Echocardiogram shows a mass (*) attached to the tricuspid valve and right atrium. The tip of a central venous catheter (arrow) is seen within the right atrium. <i>LA</i> = left atrium, <i>LV</i> = left ventricle. <b>(b)</b> Transaxial CT image shows a low-attenuation mass (*) in the right atrium <i>(RA)</i> that is associated with the tip of the central venous catheter (arrows). <b>(c, d)</b> Transaxial bright blood <b>(c)</b> and contrast-enhanced <b>(d)</b> MR images show a nonenhancing right atrial mass (*) that protrudes into the RV during diastole, a finding consistent with thrombus. The patient began anticoagulation therapy. A follow-up echocardiogram obtained 4 days later (not shown) showed improved flow around the thrombus and interval decrease in the thrombus size. <i>RA</i> = right atrium.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.344135163&amp;id=fig10a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.344135163/asset/images/large/rg.344135163.fig10b.jpeg" height="581" width="737" aria-labelledby="fig10b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10b</span> Thrombus in a 7-year-old girl with hemoglobin SS disease and a right atrial mass seen at routine echocardiography. <i>RV</i> = right ventricle. <b>(a)</b> Echocardiogram shows a mass (*) attached to the tricuspid valve and right atrium. The tip of a central venous catheter (arrow) is seen within the right atrium. <i>LA</i> = left atrium, <i>LV</i> = left ventricle. <b>(b)</b> Transaxial CT image shows a low-attenuation mass (*) in the right atrium <i>(RA)</i> that is associated with the tip of the central venous catheter (arrows). <b>(c, d)</b> Transaxial bright blood <b>(c)</b> and contrast-enhanced <b>(d)</b> MR images show a nonenhancing right atrial mass (*) that protrudes into the RV during diastole, a finding consistent with thrombus. The patient began anticoagulation therapy. A follow-up echocardiogram obtained 4 days later (not shown) showed improved flow around the thrombus and interval decrease in the thrombus size. <i>RA</i> = right atrium.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.344135163&amp;id=fig10b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.344135163/asset/images/large/rg.344135163.fig10c.jpeg" height="655" width="735" aria-labelledby="fig10c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10c</span> Thrombus in a 7-year-old girl with hemoglobin SS disease and a right atrial mass seen at routine echocardiography. <i>RV</i> = right ventricle. <b>(a)</b> Echocardiogram shows a mass (*) attached to the tricuspid valve and right atrium. The tip of a central venous catheter (arrow) is seen within the right atrium. <i>LA</i> = left atrium, <i>LV</i> = left ventricle. <b>(b)</b> Transaxial CT image shows a low-attenuation mass (*) in the right atrium <i>(RA)</i> that is associated with the tip of the central venous catheter (arrows). <b>(c, d)</b> Transaxial bright blood <b>(c)</b> and contrast-enhanced <b>(d)</b> MR images show a nonenhancing right atrial mass (*) that protrudes into the RV during diastole, a finding consistent with thrombus. The patient began anticoagulation therapy. A follow-up echocardiogram obtained 4 days later (not shown) showed improved flow around the thrombus and interval decrease in the thrombus size. <i>RA</i> = right atrium.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.344135163&amp;id=fig10c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.344135163/asset/images/large/rg.344135163.fig10d.jpeg" height="655" width="737" aria-labelledby="fig10d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10d</span> Thrombus in a 7-year-old girl with hemoglobin SS disease and a right atrial mass seen at routine echocardiography. <i>RV</i> = right ventricle. <b>(a)</b> Echocardiogram shows a mass (*) attached to the tricuspid valve and right atrium. The tip of a central venous catheter (arrow) is seen within the right atrium. <i>LA</i> = left atrium, <i>LV</i> = left ventricle. <b>(b)</b> Transaxial CT image shows a low-attenuation mass (*) in the right atrium <i>(RA)</i> that is associated with the tip of the central venous catheter (arrows). <b>(c, d)</b> Transaxial bright blood <b>(c)</b> and contrast-enhanced <b>(d)</b> MR images show a nonenhancing right atrial mass (*) that protrudes into the RV during diastole, a finding consistent with thrombus. The patient began anticoagulation therapy. A follow-up echocardiogram obtained 4 days later (not shown) showed improved flow around the thrombus and interval decrease in the thrombus size. <i>RA</i> = right atrium.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.344135163&amp;id=fig10d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.344135163/asset/images/large/rg.344135163.fig11a.jpeg" height="668" width="855" aria-labelledby="fig11a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11a</span> Pericardial cyst in a 5-year-old boy with precursor T-cell lymphoblastic leukemia who presented for evaluation of persistent pneumonia. <b>(a)</b> Chest radiograph shows an opacity (arrows) obscuring the right heart border. The opacity had been persistent on multiple previous chest radiographs. <b>(b)</b> Transaxial CT image obtained to evaluate possible persistent right middle pneumonia shows a circumscribed fluid-attenuation lesion (*) abutting the right atrium <i>(RA)</i>, a finding consistent with a pericardial cyst. <i>RV</i> = right ventricle.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.344135163&amp;id=fig11a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.344135163/asset/images/large/rg.344135163.fig11b.jpeg" height="668" width="822" aria-labelledby="fig11b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11b</span> Pericardial cyst in a 5-year-old boy with precursor T-cell lymphoblastic leukemia who presented for evaluation of persistent pneumonia. <b>(a)</b> Chest radiograph shows an opacity (arrows) obscuring the right heart border. The opacity had been persistent on multiple previous chest radiographs. <b>(b)</b> Transaxial CT image obtained to evaluate possible persistent right middle pneumonia shows a circumscribed fluid-attenuation lesion (*) abutting the right atrium <i>(RA)</i>, a finding consistent with a pericardial cyst. <i>RV</i> = right ventricle.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.344135163&amp;id=fig11b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.344135163/asset/images/large/rg.344135163.fig12a.jpeg" height="765" width="850" aria-labelledby="fig12a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12a</span> Left ventricular diverticulum in a 5-year-old girl with asthma. <b>(a)</b> Chest radiograph shows a mass (arrows) at the heart apex. <b>(b, c)</b> Oblique coronal <b>(b)</b> and transaxial <b>(c)</b> CT images demonstrate a saccular structure (*) off the left ventricular apex. The structure is connected to the left ventricle <i>(LV)</i> via a small inlet (arrows) and is filled with contrast material, findings consistent with a congenital left ventricular diverticulum. Cardiac catheterization confirmed a discrete contractile diverticulum at the ventricular apex, with a narrow inlet. Surgical resection was recommended because of the risk for emboli, diverticulum rupture, and arrhythmia. <i>RV</i> = right ventricle.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.344135163&amp;id=fig12a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.344135163/asset/images/large/rg.344135163.fig12b.jpeg" height="753" width="838" aria-labelledby="fig12b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12b</span> Left ventricular diverticulum in a 5-year-old girl with asthma. <b>(a)</b> Chest radiograph shows a mass (arrows) at the heart apex. <b>(b, c)</b> Oblique coronal <b>(b)</b> and transaxial <b>(c)</b> CT images demonstrate a saccular structure (*) off the left ventricular apex. The structure is connected to the left ventricle <i>(LV)</i> via a small inlet (arrows) and is filled with contrast material, findings consistent with a congenital left ventricular diverticulum. Cardiac catheterization confirmed a discrete contractile diverticulum at the ventricular apex, with a narrow inlet. Surgical resection was recommended because of the risk for emboli, diverticulum rupture, and arrhythmia. <i>RV</i> = right ventricle.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.344135163&amp;id=fig12b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.344135163/asset/images/large/rg.344135163.fig12c.jpeg" height="753" width="837" aria-labelledby="fig12c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12c</span> Left ventricular diverticulum in a 5-year-old girl with asthma. <b>(a)</b> Chest radiograph shows a mass (arrows) at the heart apex. <b>(b, c)</b> Oblique coronal <b>(b)</b> and transaxial <b>(c)</b> CT images demonstrate a saccular structure (*) off the left ventricular apex. The structure is connected to the left ventricle <i>(LV)</i> via a small inlet (arrows) and is filled with contrast material, findings consistent with a congenital left ventricular diverticulum. Cardiac catheterization confirmed a discrete contractile diverticulum at the ventricular apex, with a narrow inlet. Surgical resection was recommended because of the risk for emboli, diverticulum rupture, and arrhythmia. <i>RV</i> = right ventricle.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.344135163&amp;id=fig12c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div></section><section id="bibliography" role="doc-bibliography"><h2>References</h2><div role="list"><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">1.</div><div id="r1" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Uzun O, Wilson DG, Vujanic GM, Parsons JM, De Giovanni JV. Cardiac tumours in children. Orphanet J Rare Dis 2007;2:article 11. <a href="http://www.ojrd.com/content/2/1/11">http://www.ojrd.com/content/2/1/11</a>. Published March 1, 2007. Accessed September 9, 2012.